\begin_body

\begin_layout Title

\series bold
\size giant
Assignment 4: 
\begin_inset Newline linebreak
\end_inset

Fourier Approximations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date

\size larger
March 10, 2021
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author

\size larger
Saurav Sachin Kale, EE19B141
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Aim
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Study the fitting of functions using the fourier series, given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{0}+\Sigma_{n=1}^{\infty}\{a_{n}cos(nx)\}+b_{n}sin(nx)\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Observe and compare the coefficients generated by direct integration, as
 well a by the method of least squares.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Observe the variation of absolute error between the coefficients calculated
 using both of these methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Procedure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We know that the fourier coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset

are given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{0}=\frac{1}{2\pi}\intop_{0}^{2\pi}f(x)dx
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=\frac{1}{\pi}\intop_{0}^{2\pi}f(x)cos(nx)dx
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{n}=\frac{1}{\pi}\intop_{0}^{2\pi}f(x)sin(nx)dx
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For the first method of direct integration, we implement the above formulae
 by integrating two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,k)=f(x)cos(kx)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x,k)=f(x)sin(kx)$
\end_inset

 and integrating them for the various values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 using the Scipy function
\begin_inset listings
lstparams "breaklines=true"
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

scipy.integrate.quad(<function_to_be_integrated>, <lower_lim>, <upper_lim>,
 <extra_args>)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Here, 
\family typewriter
<function_to_be_integrated>
\family default
 is either 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,k)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x,k)$
\end_inset

.
 The limits of the integrals will be from 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,2\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\family typewriter
<extra_args>
\family default
, we shall specify the value of k, since k is not the variable over which
 we are integrating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Using a loop, we can compute all the fourier coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a_{0},a_{1},...,a_{25}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{b_{1},b_{2},...,b_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For the second menthod of least squares, we now define a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 going from 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,2\pi)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $400$
\end_inset

 steps.
 Evaluating the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 at each 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we get another vector 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Now, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in x$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{0}+\Sigma_{n=1}^{25}a_{n}cos(nx_{i})+\Sigma_{n=1}^{25}b_{n}sin(nx_{i})\approx f(x_{i})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This expression can be written in matrix form as shown below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{cccccc}
1 & cos(x_{1}) & sin(x_{1}) & ... & cos(25x_{1}) & sin(25x_{1})\\
1 & cos(x_{2}) & sin(x_{2}) & ... & cos(25x_{2}) & sin(25x_{2})\\
... & ... & ... & ... & ... & ...\\
1 & cos(x_{400}) & sin(x_{400}) & ... & cos(25x_{400}) & sin(25x_{400})
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{0}\\
a_{1}\\
b_{1}\\
...\\
a_{25}\\
b_{25}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
f(x_{1})\\
f(x_{2})\\
...\\
f(x_{400})
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Ac=b
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can now use the method of least squares in order to compute the matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 We will use the following Scipy function for this:
\family typewriter

\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

c = scipy.lstsq(A, b)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Absolute error or deviation is obtained by subtracting the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset

 calculated from direct integration from the values calculated by least
 squares and taking absolute value.
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Plotting the functions in interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[-2\pi,4\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 The expected fourier series plots will be repeated segments of the function
 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,2\pi)$
\end_inset

, since we have calculated the fourier series assuming the function is periodic
 with period 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename coscos_real_expected.png
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $cos(cos(x))$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and the expected fourier series plot
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Note that the above function and the expected fourier plot are identical.
 This is because function itself is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 periodic.
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename expx_real_expected.png
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and the expected fourier series plot in semilogy scale
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

This function is not periodic, therefore its expected fourier transform
 is not identical to the function.
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In order to compute the fourier series we have created a class called Fourier,
 defined as shown below:
\begin_inset listings
lstparams "breaklines=true"
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

class Fourier:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	# class attributes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    f = None
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    u = None
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    v = None
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    numCoeffs = 51
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    cosineCoeffs = []
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    sineCoeffs = []
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    Fseries = None
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	# constructor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    def __init__(self, _f, _numCoeffs = 51):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

        self.f = _f
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

        self.numCoeffs = _numCoeffs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

        self.u = lambda x, k : _f(x)*np.cos(x*k)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

        self.v = lambda x, k : _f(x)*np.sin(x*k)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

        self.cosineCoeffs.clear()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

        self.sineCoeffs.clear()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	# calculating a_i
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    def calcUk(self):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

       print("Cosine")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

        for k in range((self.numCoeffs + 1) // 2):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

            fourierCoeff = (1/np.pi) * float(integrate.quad(self.u, 0, 2*np.pi,
 args=(k))[0])
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

            self.cosineCoeffs.append(fourierCoeff)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

        print(self.cosineCoeffs)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	# calculating b_i
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    def calcVk(self):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

        print("Sine")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

        for k in range(1, (self.numCoeffs + 1) // 2):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

            fourierCoeff = (1/np.pi) * float(integrate.quad(self.v, 0, 2*np.pi,
 args=(k))[0])
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

            self.sineCoeffs.append(fourierCoeff)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

        print(self.sineCoeffs)
\end_layout

\end_inset

The coefficients are stored in the two arrays, namely 
\family typewriter
cosineCoeffs
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
sineCoeffs
\family default
.
 The functions 
\family typewriter
calcUk
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
calcVk
\family default
 calculate these values and populate these arrays with the values.
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

