\begin_layout Enumerate
Coefficients are zero for 
\begin_inset Formula $cos(cos(x))$
\end_inset

 since it is an even function.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
cos(cos(-x))=cos(cos(x))
\]

\end_inset

 We know that an even function has a cosine fourier series.
 Therefore all the sine coefficients are zero (here they are almost negligible
 but nonzero, most likely due to rounding errors)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The closer a function is to a sinusoid, the lower the number of terms having
 appreciable contribution to the series.
 
\begin_inset Formula $cos(cos(x))$
\end_inset

 is very close to a sinusoid, while 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset

 is not even periodic, let alone close to a sinusoid.
 Therefore the coefficients decay quickly for 
\begin_inset Formula $cos(cos(x))$
\end_inset

 and slowly for 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If we attempt to calculate the fourier series coefficient for general case:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=\frac{1}{\pi}\intop_{0}^{2\pi}e^{x}cos(nx)dx
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\frac{1}{\pi}(\frac{e^{2\pi}-1}{n^{2}+1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
taking log on both sides
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
log(a_{n})=log(\frac{e^{2\pi}-1}{\pi})+log(n^{2}+1)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
log(a_{n})\approx log(\frac{e^{2\pi}-1}{\pi})+2log(n)
\]

\end_inset

We can perform similar analysis for 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}.$
\end_inset

 This explains why the loglog plot of 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset

 coefficients is linear.
 Now let us look at 
\begin_inset Formula $cos(cos(x))$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=\frac{1}{\pi}\intop_{0}^{2\pi}cos(cos(x))cos(nx)dx
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\approx2\pi cos(1)+\frac{1}{6}(2\pi)^{3}(sin(1)âˆ’n^{2}cos(1))+...
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
taking log on both sides we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
log(a_{n})\propto-n
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
Therefore semilogy plot is linear for 
\begin_inset Formula $cos(cos(x))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using 
\family typewriter
scipy.linalg.lstsq
\family default
, we determine the best fit coefficients satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $Ac=b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

