\begin_layout Enumerate
The answers by least squares matches quite closely for the 
\begin_inset Formula $cos(cos(x))$
\end_inset

 case, but has significant deviations for 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The appreciable deviation for 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset

 is expected, because the function, when made periodic by replicating the
 portion from 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,2\pi)$
\end_inset

 contains discontinuities.
 Due to Gibbs Phenomenon, the values of the obtained Fourier Series synthesis
 vary wildly after encountering a discontinuity.
 Therefore, the coefficients obtained from the method of least squares should
 deviate significantly from the real values (those obtained from method
 of least squares), since our 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 matrix contained the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=e^{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in x$
\end_inset

, and not of the fourier synthesis.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

We now find and plot the deviation, obtained by the absolute value of the
 difference between coefficients calculated by both methods.
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename deviation_exp.png
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Absolute difference between fourier coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset

 calculated using direct integration and method of least squares
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

From the graph, the largest deviation for coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset

 is roughly 
\begin_inset Formula $1.332$
\end_inset

, which is significant.
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename deviation_coscos.png
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Absolute difference between fourier coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $cos(cos(x))$
\end_inset

 calculated using direct integration and method of least squares
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

From the graph, the maximum deviation for coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $cos(cos(x))$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $2.67\times10^{-15}$
\end_inset

which is almost negligible.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

This was done using vectors in the following manner:
\family typewriter

\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

deviation = [abs(i) for i in (f - c)]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 
\family default
and
\family typewriter
 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 
\family default
are vectors of size 51, containing the coefficients calculated by each of
 the two methods.
 A simple subtraction does this operation for all the 51 coefficients at
 once.
 Then we also take absolute value for each result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We now perform the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $Ac$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 (the actual fourier series).
 We plot this vs.
 x with green circles on top of figure (1) and (2) to get the following
 plots:
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fitted_exp.png
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
